[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Incremental development builds up a system by partitioning the system specified in the requirements documents into subsystems by functionality and then defining releases that begin with one small, functional subsystem and add functionality with each new release.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In incremental development , the system as specified in the requirements  documents  is  partitioned  into  subsystems  by  functionality. The  releases  are defined by beginning with one small,functional subsystem and then adding functionality with each new release.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Each increment is easier to test and correct because faults are more likely to be found in the new code, not in the called units that have already been tested and deemed correct.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each increment is easier to test and correct because faults are more likely to be found in the new code, not in the called units that have already been tested and deemed correct.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Incremental development allows having a working version of a system subset to demonstrate to customers frequently, which helps maintain high morale among developers as they make visible progress on the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In addition, we always have a working version of a system subset to demonstrate to our customer. Moreover, morale among developers is high, because they  frequently  make  visible  progress  on  the  system",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Incremental development slowly builds up to full functionality with each new release, as illustrated in the top part of Figure 2.9.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The top of Figure 2.9 shows how incremental development slowly builds up to full functionality with each new release.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_572_573_146"
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Iterative development delivers a full system at the very beginning and then changes the functionality of each subsystem with each new release.",
        "citations": [
