[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook argues that high-level Petri nets are better suited than state-machine models for representing processes like an emergency room triage because Petri nets can model concurrency and synchronization of multiple events whose order of occurrence is not important.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "These features of concurrency and synchronization are especially useful for modeling events whose order of occurrence is not important. Consider the emergency room in a hospital. Before a patient can be treated, several events must occur... The events occur in no particular order, but all must occur before a team of doctors begins a more thorough examination.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A state-machine model might specify only a single order of events, thereby excluding several acceptable behaviors, or it might specify all possible sequences of events, resulting in an overly complex model for a relatively simple problem.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A state-machine model of the emergency room might specify only a single order of events, thereby excluding several acceptable behaviors, or it might specify all possible sequences of events, resulting in an overly complex model for a relatively simple problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A Petri net model of the same emergency room nicely avoids both of these problems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A Petri net model of the emergency room nicely avoids both of these problems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using the Critical Path Method (CPM), a delay in an activity that has zero slack time pushes all subsequent critical path activities forward, forcing them to be late as well if there is no slack.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the critical path has no slack, there is no margin for error when performing the activities along its route. Notice what happens when an activity on the critical path begins late (i.e., later than its earliest start time). The late start pushes all subsequent critical path activities forward, forcing them to be late, too, if there is no slack.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This logical effect means that the projected staff-days on a resource histogram would also be pushed forward, reflecting the delay in the schedule for the critical path activities.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The specific term for the path that contains these zero-slack activities is the 'critical path'.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the critical path has no slack, there is no margin for error when performing the activities along its route.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

