[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The primary development goal of building a throwaway rapid prototype during the requirements elicitation phase is to quickly learn more about the problem or the proposed solution by creating a 'quick-and-dirty' software that may be poorly structured and inefficient but helps answer questions about the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software. This approach allows us to write 'quick-and-dirty' software that is poorly structured, inefficient, with no error checking-that, in fact, may be a facade that does not implement any of the desired functionality-but that gets quickly to the heart of questions we have about the problem or about a proposed solution.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the primary goal of building a throwaway rapid prototype during the software architecture design phase is to explore design issues and assess the feasibility or particular characteristics of a proposed design, often leading to discarding the prototype and building the actual system from scratch.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues, we may not give its development the same careful attention that we would give to a real system. For this reason, we frequently discard the prototype and build the actual system from scratch, rather than try to salvage parts from the prototype. In these cases, the throw-away prototype is meant to be discarded; its development is intended only to assess the feasibility or particular characteristics in a proposed design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the requirements phase prototype focuses on understanding and clarifying the problem and requirements, the architecture phase prototype focuses on evaluating design alternatives and feasibility of architectural decisions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution... Once our questions are answered, we throw away the prototype software and start engineering the software that will be delivered.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a prototype is intended only to explore design issues, we may not give its development the same careful attention that we would give to a real system. For this reason, we frequently discard the prototype and build the actual system from scratch, rather than try to salvage parts from the prototype.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A Parnas table represents conditions and states in a tabular form where rows and columns define predicates that specify different cases, and the internal table entries represent the possible function results for those cases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The column and row headers are predicates used to specify cases, and the internal table entries store the possible function results. Thus, each internal table entry represents a distinct case in the function's definition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The Parnas table uses purely mathematical expressions for inputs and outputs, and the table entries specify either input conditions or output values for cases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Unlike decision tables, the inputs and outputs of a Parnas table are purely mathematical expressions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a formal Z specification schema for the \"Return\" operation structures the representation into two sections: the top section indicates whether the operation modifies or queries the system state and identifies inputs and outputs, while the bottom section specifies pre-conditions and post-conditions using logical expressions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The top section of an operation schema indicates whether the operation modifies ( D ) or simply queries ( X ) the system state, and identifies the inputs (?) and outputs (!) of the operation. The bottom section of an operation schema specifies the operation's pre-conditions and post-conditions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The Z schema uses unprimed variables to represent values before the operation and primed variables for values after the operation, with post-conditions expressed as updates or constraints on system state variables.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In operations that modify the system state, unprimed variables represent variable values before the operation is performed, and primed variables represent values following the operation. ... The post-conditions update the Catalogue to include the new Item, and specify that the other library variables do not change value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, structurally, the Parnas table organizes conditions and results in a matrix format focusing on case distinctions via predicates, while the Z schema organizes conditions and state changes in a logical, modular format separating inputs, outputs, pre-conditions, and post-conditions with explicit state variable updates.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The column and row headers are predicates used to specify cases, and the internal table entries store the possible function results. ... The top section of an operation schema indicates whether the operation modifies ( D ) or simply queries ( X ) the system state, and identifies the inputs (?) and outputs (!) of the operation. The bottom section of an operation schema specifies the operation's pre-conditions and post-conditions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "structure interpretation"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The \"hot standby\" redundancy fault-recovery tactic failed during the Ariane-5 maiden flight because it was designed under the assumption that hardware and software failures behave similarly, which is not the case.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Ariane-5 included a number of redundant components in which both the hardware equipment and the associated software were identical. In most cases, one of the components was supposed to be active; the other was to stay in 'hot standby' mode, ready to become the active component if the current active component failed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook explains that hardware failures are independent, meaning if one hardware unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. However, software failures tend to be logical errors that affect all copies of a software component simultaneously because they share the same faults and respond similarly to bad input.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Hardware failures are independent: if one unit fails, the standby unit is usually unaffected and can take over as the active unit. By contrast, software faults tend to be logical errors, so all copies of a software component have the same set of faults. Moreover, even if the software is not the underlying cause of a failure, replicated software components are likely to exhibit the same bad behavior in response to bad input.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "As a result, the hot standby redundancy in Ariane-5 was likely to recover only from hardware failures, not software failures. This was demonstrated in the Ariane-5 failure where both inertial reference systems suffered the same overflow error simultaneously, causing both units to fail.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For these reasons, the hot standby redundancy in Ariane-5 is likely to recover only from hardware failures. ... This was the situation with the failed inertial reference systems (SRIs) on the Ariane-5: both units suffered the same overflow error, simultaneously.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A 'pure' layered system restricts each software unit in a given layer to access only the units in the same layer and the services offered by the interface to the layer immediately below it, which enforces explicit interfaces and reduces coupling between layers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a 'pure' layered system, a software unit in a given layer can access only the other units in the same layer and services offered by the interface to the layer immediately below it.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This design minimizes dependencies among software units by ensuring that changes in one layer affect at most only the two adjacent layers, thus reducing the likelihood that a change will ripple to other units.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, because a layer can interact only with its neighboring layers, layer modification is relatively easy; such changes should affect at most only the two adjacent layers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The OSI model exemplifies this by providing each layer with a clear interface that hides the implementation details of the services it offers to the layer above, supporting low coupling and explicit interfaces.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the OSI example, each layer raises the level of abstraction of the communication services that are available to the next layer, and hides all of the details about how those services are implemented.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "By using explicit interfaces and limiting access to adjacent layers, the layered architecture reduces dependencies and coupling, which aligns with tactics for minimizing the impact on indirectly affected software units when a layer is modified.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By lowering coupling, we reduce the likelihood that a change to one unit will ripple to other units.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If a unit interacts with other units only through their interfaces (e.g., calling public access methods), then changes to one unit will not spread beyond the unit's boundary unless its interface changes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

