[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to McCall's quality model, \"Usability\" is linked to internal criteria such as \"Operability\" and \"Training\".",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_188_188_57"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers can use fit criteria to transform subjective quality requirements like Usability into objectively testable specifications by quantifying the extent to which each requirement must be met, thus creating objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Robertson and Robertson (1999) point out that testability (which they call 'measurability') can be addressed when requirements are being elicited. The idea is to quantify the extent to which each requirement must be met. These fit criteria form objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, subjective quality requirements like usability can be evaluated using metrics or focus groups, such as: \"75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system\" or \"After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.\"",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What about more subjective quality requirements, like usability or maintainability? In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria: - 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system. - After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

