        "segment": "The initial risk exposure is calculated by multiplying the risk probability by the potential loss impact.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can quantify the effects of the risks we identify by multiplying the risk impact by the risk probability, to yield the risk exposure.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Given a risk probability of 0.25 and a loss impact of $500,000, the initial risk exposure is 0.25 × $500,000 = $125,000.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, if the likelihood that the requirements will change after design is 0.3, and the cost to redesign to new requirements is $50,000, then the risk exposure is $15,000.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To determine the risk reduction leverage, the project manager must calculate the difference in risk exposure before and after the risk reduction action, then divide that difference by the cost of reducing the risk.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To aid decision making about risk reduction, we must take into account the cost of reducing the risk. We call risk leverage the difference in risk exposure divided by the cost of reducing the risk.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Mathematically, risk reduction leverage = (risk exposure before reduction - risk exposure after reduction) / cost of reducing the risk.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "risk reduction leverage is If the leverage value is not high enough to justify the action, then we can look for other less costly or more effective reduction techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "If the cost of the mitigation strategy is $50,000, the project manager needs to estimate the new risk exposure after mitigation to complete the calculation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If the leverage value is not high enough to justify the action, then we can look for other less costly or more effective reduction techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "process reasoning"
    }
]

