            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, the larger the staff (reflected in staff size), the more time is devoted to communication among project members (communication overhead).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A company justifies the initial higher development costs of creating a core asset base for a software product line through financial analysis methods such as Net Present Value (NPV).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The acceptance rule for NPV is simple: invest in a project if its NPV is greater than zero.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The reuse requires considerable upfront costs for design and documentation, but the long-term costs are less than normal.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This means that although the upfront investment in reusable design is high, the long-term savings and returns from reuse can make the investment worthwhile.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The reuse requires considerable upfront costs for design and documentation, but the long-term costs are less than normal.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Strategically, the company plans the product line from the beginning as a product family with a core asset base that includes reusable assets such as requirements, designs, code, and test cases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Their simultaneous development is planned from the beginning. The family's commonalities are described as a collection of reusable assets (including requirements, designs, code, and test cases), all stored in a core asset base.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "This approach allows development to resemble an assembly line where components are adapted from the core asset base rather than developed from scratch, reducing overall development cost and effort.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "development resembles an assembly line: many of the components can be adapted from components in the core asset base and then plugged together, rather than developing each from scratch.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding the scoping of product commonality, it is a challenging problem that affects the return on investment for derived products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Product-line scoping is a challenging problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The effects of scoping product commonality on return on investment include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Product-line scoping is a challenging problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "If the scope is too narrow (high commonality), some profitable products outside the scope may be excluded.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we strive for some notion of optimal commonality among the products (e.g.,by insisting on reusing 80 percent of the code), we may exclude some interesting and profitable products that lie outside of the scope.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "If the scope is too broad (low commonality), the degree of reuse decreases, reducing the savings and benefits from the product line.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "if we try to include any product that looks related, we reduce the degree of commonality among the derived products, and consequently the amount of savings that can be achieved.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "A successful product line balances these extremes with a core architecture that strongly supports the more promising products to be built.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A successful product line lies somewhere in the middle of these two extremes, with a core architecture that strongly supports the more promising products that we want to build.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The return on investment for derived products depends on how much of the product's architecture is shared with the product line's core asset base.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "each derived product's architecture must start with the product-line architecture, incorporating a significant fraction of its software units from the product line's core asset base.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The more the derived product shares with the core asset base, the greater the savings and productivity improvements; conversely, less commonality means the derived product's development resembles a new product, reducing the return on investment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The less the final derived product has in common with the product line, the more the derived product's development will resemble a completely new (i.e., nonderived) product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In the operational specification process model, the \"Transformed Specification\" represents an implementation-oriented form derived from the operational specification, which is problem-oriented and executable to demonstrate system behavior before design begins.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 2.6 illustrates how an operational specification works.Notice that the operational specification is similar to prototyping; the process enables user and developer to examine requirements early on.",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_553_562_142"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "the operational specification is evaluated or executed in a way that demonstrates the behavior of the system.That is,once the requirements are specified,they can be enacted using a software package, so their implications can be assessed before design begins.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "TRANSFORMED SPECIFICATION (implementation-oriented)",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_553_562_142"
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the transition between a throwaway prototype and an evolutionary prototype during requirements engineering involves a shift from a quickly built, low-quality software used only to explore and understand requirements (throwaway) to a more carefully developed software that is intended to be part of the final product and meet quality requirements (evolutionary).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype is software that is developed to learn more about a problem or about a proposed solution, and that is never intended to be part of the delivered software.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In contrast, an evolutionary prototype is software that is developed not only to help us answer questions but also to be incorporated into the final product.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "As such, we have to be much more careful in its development, because this software has to eventually exhibit the quality requirements (e.g., response rate, modularity) of the final product, and these qualities cannot be retrofitted.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Conceptually, the \"Transformed Specification\" in the operational specification model is a formal step in the development process that moves from a problem-oriented executable specification to an implementation-oriented specification, serving as a bridge to the delivered system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Using automated support, the transformational process applies a series of transformations to change a specification into a deliverable system (Balzer 1981a).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The sequence of transformations and the decisions they reflect are kept as a formal development record.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Meanwhile, the transition from throwaway to evolutionary prototyping is a conceptual shift in the purpose and quality of the prototype software during requirements engineering, rather than a formal transformation of specifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Both techniques are sometimes called rapid prototyping , because they involve building  software  in  order  to  answer  questions  about  the requirements .",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A throwaway prototype ... may be a facade that does not implement any of the desired functionality-but that gets quickly to the heart of questions we have about the problem or about a proposed solution.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An evolutionary prototype is software that is developed not only to help us answer questions but also to be incorporated into the final product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A data-flow diagram (DFD) models functionality and the flow of data from one function to another, where data stores represent repositories or databases of information, and actors represent entities that provide input data or receive output results.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A data-flow diagram (DFD) models functionality and the flow of data from one function to another. ... Data that persist beyond their use in a single computation (e.g., information about patrons' outstanding fines) can be saved in a data store -a formal repository or database of information-that is represented by two parallel bars. Data sources or sinks, represented by rectangles, are actors : entities that provide input data or receive the output results.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In the context of COCOMO II estimation, the data stores and actors identified in the DFD would influence the complexity weights used to calculate Application Points in Stage 1 by representing the system's data repositories and external interfaces, respectively, which are key factors in determining the system's size and complexity.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Specifically, data stores correspond to internal logical files or data groups that the system manages, and actors correspond to external inputs and outputs, both of which are components used in calculating Application Points. The number and complexity of these elements directly affect the weighting factors applied during the calculation.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, the identification of data stores and actors in the DFD provides a structured way to enumerate and classify the system's data and interface elements, which are essential inputs for determining the complexity weights in the Application Points calculation of COCOMO II Stage 1.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "According to McCall's quality model, flexibility is an important external quality factor related to modifiability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 1.5 is an example of an early quality model built by McCall and his colleagues to show how external quality factors (on the left-hand side) relate to product quality criteria (on the right-hand side).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To achieve flexibility by minimizing the number of indirectly affected software units when a change occurs, the architect should apply modifiability tactics that focus on reducing coupling and managing interfaces effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Given a particular change to a system, Bass, Clements, and Kazman (2003) distinguish between the software units that are directly affected by the change and those that are indirectly affected. The directly affected units are those whose responsibilities change to accommodate a system modification. We can structure our code to minimize the number of units requiring change. The indirectly affected units are those whose responsibilities do not change, but whose implementations must be revised to accommodate changes in the directly affected units.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The specific modifiability tactics to minimize indirectly affected units include:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Different architectural styles address different aspects of modifiability, so we must know how to select the styles that address our specific modifiability goals.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Reducing coupling between software units to limit the ripple effect of changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Tactics for minimizing the number of software units directly affected by a software change focus on clustering anticipated changes in the design.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Managing and designing clear, stable interfaces to encapsulate changes and isolate the impact of modifications.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Identify design decisions that are most likely to change, and encapsulate each in its own software unit.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Establishing specific fit criteria for subjective quality requirements like usability during the requirements phase allows these requirements to be quantified and tested objectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Robertson and Robertson (1999) point out that testability (which they call 'measurability') can be addressed when requirements are being elicited. The idea is to quantify the extent to which each requirement must be met. These fit criteria form objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What about more subjective quality requirements, like usability or maintainability? In these cases, developers use focus groups or metrics to evaluate fit criteria: - 75% of users shall judge the new system to be as usable as the existing system. - After training, 90% of users shall be able to process a new account within 5 minutes.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "By having these quantified fit criteria, the parameters such as risk impact and risk probability used in risk exposure and risk reduction leverage calculations during project planning can be more accurately estimated.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The risk exposure is computed from the risk impact and the risk probability, so we must estimate each of these risk aspects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This means that the risk parameters are no longer vague or subjective but are based on measurable criteria, which improves the precision of risk management activities and helps in making informed decisions about risk reduction strategies.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Robertson and Robertson (1999) point out that testability (which they call 'measurability') can be addressed when requirements are being elicited. The idea is to quantify the extent to which each requirement must be met. These fit criteria form objective standards for judging whether a proposed solution satisfies the requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The risk exposure is computed from the risk impact and the risk probability, so we must estimate each of these risk aspects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A highly hierarchical Chief Programmer team structure theoretically faces fewer communication bottlenecks than a loosely structured, egoless team because it is designed for projects with high certainty, stability, uniformity, and repetition, which require little communication among project members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A National Science Foundation (1983) investigation found that projects with a high degree of certainty, stability, uniformity, and repetition can be accomplished more effectively by a hierarchical organizational structure such as the chief programmer team. These projects require little communication among project members, so they are well-suited to an organization that stresses rules, specialization, formality, and a clear definition of organizational hierarchy.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, a loosely structured, egoless team is more democratic and encourages open communication and participation in decision making, which can increase communication overhead and potential bottlenecks.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An egoless team structure is democratic, and all team members vote on a decision, whether it concerns design considerations or testing techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When there is much uncertainty involved in a project, a more democratic approach may be better. Here, participation in decision making, a loosely defined hierarchy, and the encouragement of open communication can be effective.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Since a tightly coupled algebraic specification notation like SDL Data implies many dependencies and interactions between modules, a hierarchical structure with clear roles and limited communication paths reduces communication bottlenecks by minimizing the need for extensive coordination among many team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 6.1 Module coupling.]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_2497_2497_611"
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A single-element cut-set (e.g., {A1}) derived from a fault-tree analysis represents a minimal event combination that could lead to the top failure in the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, if any member of the cut-set is a singleton event set, {A i }, then the top failure could be caused by a single event, A i .",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In terms of the system's internal developer view, this single event corresponds to a fault, which is an inside view of the system seen by developers as a flaw or defect caused by a human error.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A fault occurs when a human makes a mistake, called an error, in performing some software activity.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, a fault is an inside view of the system, as seen by the eyes of the developers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the system's observable behavior perspective, the fault may manifest as a failure, which is a departure from the system's required behavior visible to users or customers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A failure is a departure from the system's required behavior.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, a fault is an inside view of the system, as seen by the eyes of the developers, whereas a failure is an outside view: a problem that the user sees.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, a single-element cut-set indicates that the top-level failure can be caused by a single fault event internally, which may or may not manifest as an observable failure depending on whether the fault conditions are met during system operation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, if any member of the cut-set is a singleton event set, {A i }, then the top failure could be caused by a single event, A i .",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "It is important to realize that not every fault corresponds to a failure, since the conditions under which a fault manifests itself as an observable failure may never be met.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Lai's process transition diagram represents states as nodes (ovals) and transitions as labeled arrows between these states, showing a direct flow from one state to another triggered by events.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_644_644_165"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 2.12 Transition diagram for a car (Lai 1991).]",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the high-level Petri net model for the library problem uses places (circles) to represent conditions or states and transitions (bars) to represent events or actions that change these states, with directed arcs connecting places and transitions to show the flow.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1458_1458_358"
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 4.13 Petri net of the library problem.]",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, structurally, Lai's diagram uses a simpler state-transition graph with states as nodes and transitions as edges, while the Petri net explicitly separates conditions (places) and events (transitions) as different types of nodes, connected by arcs to model concurrency and synchronization.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Modeling the complete system's dynamic behavior using Message Sequence Charts (MSCs) in a pure publish-subscribe architectural style with implicit invocation is inherently difficult or misleading because the behavior of a publishing component depends on which subscribing components are monitoring its events.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Publish-subscribe systems are difficult to test, because the behavior of a publishing component will depend on which subscribing components are monitoring its events.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Thus, we cannot test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, we cannot test the component in isolation and infer its correctness in an integrated system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "Because publish-subscribe components know nothing about each other and interact only by broadcasting and reacting to events, the interactions are indirect and asynchronous, making it challenging to capture the exact sequence and dependencies of interactions in MSCs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In contrast to client-server and P2P components, publish-subscribe components know nothing about each other. Instead, the publishing component simply announces events and then waits for interested components to react; each subscribing component simply reacts to event announcements, regardless of how they are published.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "causal reasoning"
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Extreme Programming (XP), the system is built to the requirements that happen to be defined at the time, with no planning or designing for possible future requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Extreme programming (XP) takes agile requirements processes to the extreme, in that the system is built to the requirements that happen to be defined at the time, with no planning or designing for possible future requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This approach in XP means that future, unanticipated requirements are not considered during initial development, which can lead to difficulties in making changes as requirements evolve.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Berry (2002a) points out that the trade-off for agile methods' flexibility is the difficulty of making changes to the system as requirements are added, deleted, or changed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, when scoping and designing a core asset base for a Software Product Line architecture, a strategic approach is taken that involves defining baseline architectures, documented scenarios, and system boundaries to guide development and accommodate future variability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Rather than use prioritized stories, the researchers found it essential to define baseline architectures, using documented scenarios to help describe key abstractions, and to define system boundaries.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This strategic planning and documentation help ensure maintainability and accommodate future requirements over the system's likely long lifespan, unlike XP's focus on immediate requirements without future planning.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documentation was used to assist in communicating among team members. Strict agile-methods advocates eschew documentation, but Drobke, Noftz, and Raghu found it to be essential. So, too, were design reviews to ensure that the software being built would be maintainable over its likely 30-year life span.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The software industry's definition of Return on Investment (ROI) primarily focuses on effort reduction and time savings, emphasizing saving time or using fewer people rather than direct cost or dollar savings.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars. That is, companies were interested in saving time or using fewer people, and their definition of return on investment reflected this focus on decreasing effort.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, the mathematical calculation of a design's \"payback period\" in a formal cost-benefit analysis is a financial measure that calculates the time it takes for an investment to return its original capital plus additional returns, often expressed in terms of dollars and discounted cash flows.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Usually, the business community uses one of three models to assess ROI: a payback model, an accounting rate-of-return model, and a discounted cash flow model.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "NPV expresses economic value in terms of total project life, regardless of scale or time frame. Since investment planning involves spending money in the future, we can think of the present value of an investment as the value today of a predicted future cash flow.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Thus, while the software industry ROI is effort- and time-based focusing on operational improvements, the payback period calculation is a formal financial metric focusing on the monetary return and timing of cash flows.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The government views ROI in terms of dollars, looking at reducing operating costs, predicting dollar savings, and calculating the cost of employing new technologies.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "On the other hand, industry viewed investment in terms of effort, rather than cost or dollars.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Usually, the business community uses one of three models to assess ROI: a payback model, an accounting rate-of-return model, and a discounted cash flow model.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": "comparison"
    }
]
